the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Percy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin):","nickname from Old French <i>percehaie</i> ‘pierce hedge’ (Old French <i>percer</i> ‘to pierce, penetrate’ + <i>haie</i> ‘hedge, fence’), perhaps with the sense of someone breaking into an enclosure. <i>Percehaie</i> is the name of one of the sons of the foxes Renart and Hermeline in the medieval French epic <i>Roman de Renart</i>, whose earliest known version is from the 1170s. The surname is older than that, but it may originate in a nickname for the fox as ‘enclosure piercer’, perhaps amounting to ‘chicken thief’.","habitational name from any of several places called Percy in Calvados, Eure, and Manche; William <i>de Perci</i>, the Domesday tenant-in-chief and under-tenant of Hugh, Earl of Chester, came from either Percy-en-Auge (Eure) or Percy (Manche)."],"variants":[{"name":"Piercey","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Piercy","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Pearcey","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Peercy","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Pearcy","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705184,"age":8,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":18,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William de Percy was born in 1088, in Alnwick, Northumberland, England. He had at least 1 son with Alice de Ros."},"et":{"1088–":"1088–Surnud","1090–1119":"1090–1119","1112–1175":"1112–1175","1088–Male":"1088–Surnud","1106":"1106","1090":"1090","1112":"1112","1088":"1088","1175":"1175","1096":"1096","1119":"1119","Alnwick, Northumberland, England":"Alnwick, Northumberland, England"},"fi":{"1088–":"1088–Kuollut","1090–1119":"1090–1119","1112–1175":"1112–1175","1088–Male":"1088–Kuollut","1106":"1106","1090":"1090","1112":"1112","1088":"1088","1175":"1175","1096":"1096","1119":"1119","Alnwick, Northumberland, England":"Alnwick, Northumberland, England"},"fr":{"1088–":"1088–Décédé","1090–1119":"1090–1119","1112–1175":"1112–1175","1088–Male":"1088–Décédé","1106":"1106","1090":"1090","1112":"1112","1088":"1088","1175":"1175","1096":"1096","1119":"1119","Alnwick, Northumberland, England":"Alnwick, Northumberland, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"William de Percy est né en 1088, à Alnwick, Northumberland, Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Alice de Ros."},"de":{"1088–":"1088–Verstorben","1090–1119":"1090–1119","1112–1175":"1112–1175","1088–Male":"1088–Verstorben